fields.description: School, instead of bringing great satisfaction, fulfillment, and confirmation of your identity, has become a joyless burden to be minimized, avoided, or escaped. You seem overwhelmed, unable to cope, and unmotivated. Perhaps you have been displaying negative attitudes towards studying, your professors, and/or schoolmates. Your academic and/or extracurricular performance might be poor.
fields.remarks: Please note that this profile is based on your current state and might change in the months to come. The causes of burnout can be quite complex and vary from one student to the next. We suggest that you speak to your Guidance Practitioner about your concerns at school.

fields.description:
You seem to be experiencing frequent exhaustion. Perhaps the major mismatch you are facing at school is a very heavy workload, usually with high demands from your professors and/or schoolmates as well as long hours. 

Nevertheless, you still find school to be meaningful, which heightens your involvement and motivation to do well. And when you succeed in accomplishing your tasks, you feel competent and effective.
fields.remarks: Please note that this profile is based on your current state and might change in the months to come. If you think you need help, feel free to discuss your concerns with your Guidance Practitioner any time.

fields.description:
You seem to be consistently cynical about studying or participating at school. Perhaps you have lost the motivation that originally attracted you to your course or the school. Although you can still manage your workload, you seem to be experiencing major difficulties in other areas of your student life, including lack of control or influence, insufficient rewards or recognition, and poor quality of relationships with your professors and/or schoolmates. Some students who have the same profile might feel constrained from doing the right thing at school, suggesting feelings of moral injury and compassion fatigue.

Nevertheless, you are ready to commit time and effort to studying or participating at school, rather than feeling too tired and overwhelmed. And when you succeed in accomplishing your tasks, you feel competent and effective.
fields.remarks: Please note that this profile is based on your current state and might change in the months to come. If you think you need help, feel free to discuss your concerns with your Guidance Practitioner any time.

fields.description:
You seem to have a negative sense of your own accomplishments at school. Perhaps your course requirements or roles at school are not intrinsically rewarding or you do not see yourself making any progress. Even if you make a real effort, the results may seem trivial, and you may have lost the confidence in your ability to make a difference.

Nevertheless, you are ready to commit time and effort to studying or participating at school, rather than feeling too tired and overwhelmed. You still find school to be meaningful, which heightens your involvement and motivation to do well.
fields.remarks: Please note that this profile is based on your current state and might change in the months to come. If you think you need help, feel free to discuss your concerns with your Guidance Practitioner any time.

fields.description:
You feel effective and successful in your accomplishments but you seem very exhausted and cynical towards school. 

Perhaps you are burdened with a very heavy workload, usually with high demands from your professors and/or schoolmates as well as long hours. 

Furthermore, it seems that you have lost the motivation that originally attracted you to your course or the school. Besides exhaustion, you may be experiencing a lack of control or influence, insufficient rewards or recognition, and poor quality of relationships with your professors and/or schoolmates. Some students who have the same profile might feel constrained from doing the right thing at school, suggesting feelings of moral injury and compassion fatigue.
